WEBVTT

00:05.881 --> 00:08.884
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:08.884 --> 00:13.847
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:13.847 --> 00:17.017
[ice crackling]

00:17.017 --> 00:18.435
<i>‐ My name is Ben Spangler.</i>

00:18.435 --> 00:19.728
When I was 15,

00:19.728 --> 00:21.271
I was hanging out
on my parents' farm,

00:21.271 --> 00:22.814
<i>and I found a bucket</i>
<i>of blacksmithing tools.</i>

00:22.814 --> 00:24.191
<i>I figured,</i>
<i>let's give it a shot.</i>

00:24.191 --> 00:25.400
<i>And I liked it so much,</i>

00:25.400 --> 00:26.860
I kept doing it ever since.

00:26.860 --> 00:28.195
<i>[rock music]</i>

00:28.195 --> 00:29.780
<i>‐ I'm Adam Jankowski,</i>

00:29.780 --> 00:31.740
and I am
from Two Creeks, Wisconsin.

00:31.740 --> 00:34.409
<i>I served in the army,</i>
<i>and during that time,</i>

00:34.409 --> 00:37.412
<i>I did deploy to Iraq in 2008.</i>

00:37.412 --> 00:39.081
I suffer from PTSD.

00:39.081 --> 00:42.960
<i>Forging has given me purpose.</i>

00:42.960 --> 00:45.254
<i>I feel safe in my forge.</i>

00:45.254 --> 00:47.381
It's like a nice comfy blanket.

00:47.381 --> 00:48.549
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:48.549 --> 00:50.259
<i>‐ Name's Kasey Kinkade.</i>

00:50.259 --> 00:52.010
I'm am American Farrier's
Association

00:52.010 --> 00:53.804
Certified Journeyman Farrier.

00:53.804 --> 00:56.390
I've watched "Forged in Fire"
for years with my wife,

00:56.390 --> 00:58.600
and I'm always screaming
at the TV.

00:58.600 --> 01:01.770
So she's like, "Put your money
where your mouth is."

01:01.770 --> 01:04.106
[chuckles]

01:04.106 --> 01:05.524
‐ My name is Josh Navarrete.

01:05.524 --> 01:06.942
<i>I was born in Mexico,</i>

01:06.942 --> 01:08.527
<i>and we came</i>
<i>to the United States</i>

01:08.527 --> 01:10.070
<i>when I was a kid.</i>

01:10.070 --> 01:12.739
<i>This is going to be</i>
<i>a huge challenge.</i>

01:12.739 --> 01:16.451
There's gonna be tears,
sweat, and probably blood,

01:16.451 --> 01:18.745
<i>but I want to go through it.</i>

01:18.745 --> 01:20.414
<i>It comes down to this:</i>

01:20.414 --> 01:21.999
I don't want to disappoint
my <i>abuelita.</i>

01:21.999 --> 01:23.458
It doesn't get any more
complicated than that.

01:23.458 --> 01:25.377
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:25.377 --> 01:27.754
[ice crackling]

01:27.754 --> 01:29.631
[crow cawing]

01:29.631 --> 01:33.802
‐ Bladesmiths, welcome
to the great outdoors.

01:33.802 --> 01:35.387
We've brought you out here
to the frozen tundra

01:35.387 --> 01:36.930
to make your lives miserable.

01:36.930 --> 01:38.974
You're here to engage
in three timed rounds

01:38.974 --> 01:40.517
of edged weapon‐making
competition

01:40.517 --> 01:42.644
designed to test every aspect
of your skills

01:42.644 --> 01:44.646
in front of a panel
of expert judges:

01:44.646 --> 01:47.482
two‐time "Forged in Fire"
champion Ben Abbott;

01:47.482 --> 01:49.776
next, historic weapons
re‐creation specialist

01:49.776 --> 01:51.486
David Baker;
and last,

01:51.486 --> 01:55.032
edged weapon specialist
Doug Marcaida.

01:55.032 --> 01:58.452
Gentlemen, you have only
hand‐crank coal forges

01:58.452 --> 01:59.661
to use today.

01:59.661 --> 02:01.079
There will be no power hammers.

02:01.079 --> 02:02.706
There will be no presses.

02:02.706 --> 02:04.916
Just good old‐fashioned
hand‐hammering.

02:04.916 --> 02:07.836
‐ We're gonna be forging
outside, and for me,

02:07.836 --> 02:09.379
I'm hoping that gives me
an edge.

02:09.379 --> 02:10.589
<i>My home forge is outside.</i>

02:10.589 --> 02:11.798
<i>I'm used to the cold.</i>

02:11.798 --> 02:14.009
I'm hoping my competitors
are not.

02:14.009 --> 02:15.886
‐ Now, there will be
no signature blade

02:15.886 --> 02:17.596
in your signature style today.

02:17.596 --> 02:20.057
Instead,
you'll be making kukris.

02:20.057 --> 02:21.600
And your kukris have to fall

02:21.600 --> 02:23.685
within the following
parameters.

02:23.685 --> 02:27.272
<i>The length of your kukri must</i>
<i>be between 11 and 13 inches.</i>

02:27.272 --> 02:30.901
<i>It must have a through‐tang,</i>
<i>an inch and a half waist,</i>

02:30.901 --> 02:32.694
<i>and a 2 1/2 inch belly.</i>

02:32.694 --> 02:34.696
And you're making them
out of this.

02:34.696 --> 02:40.118
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:40.118 --> 02:41.620
Snowmobile.

02:41.620 --> 02:43.955
Gentlemen, this snowmobile
is comprised

02:43.955 --> 02:45.707
of a lot
of different materials.

02:45.707 --> 02:47.250
Your challenge is to figure out

02:47.250 --> 02:48.960
what the high carbon steel is,

02:48.960 --> 02:52.839
salvage that high carbon steel
to make your kukri.

02:52.839 --> 02:56.009
<i>‐ This is re‐donk‐ulous,</i>
<i>but it's the competition.</i>

02:56.009 --> 02:57.594
<i>This is "Forged in Fire."</i>

02:57.594 --> 03:00.722
They throw a curveball
at you with a slider.

03:00.722 --> 03:02.182
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:02.182 --> 03:03.850
‐ In the second round,
you'll attach handles

03:03.850 --> 03:05.602
to those kukris so that we can
test them for strength

03:05.602 --> 03:08.313
and durability
in an ice block chop

03:08.313 --> 03:09.690
and for edge retention

03:09.690 --> 03:12.234
in a climbing rope slice.

03:12.234 --> 03:13.527
You'll have three hours
in this round

03:13.527 --> 03:14.986
in which to complete
your work.

03:14.986 --> 03:16.822
After this first round
of competition,

03:16.822 --> 03:18.782
after the judges have looked
at your work,

03:18.782 --> 03:20.409
one of you will be eliminated

03:20.409 --> 03:22.786
without ever stepping
into The Forge.

03:22.786 --> 03:25.372
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your three hours starts...

03:25.372 --> 03:27.249
now.

03:27.249 --> 03:29.167
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:29.167 --> 03:32.504
You got to want it bad to come
here in these conditions

03:32.504 --> 03:36.550
and go after a kukri
on a day like today.

03:36.550 --> 03:38.885
It is cold, it is frozen,

03:38.885 --> 03:41.221
and it is a tough shape

03:41.221 --> 03:42.722
to make.

03:42.722 --> 03:45.600
‐ On three.
‐ One, two, three!

03:45.600 --> 03:46.935
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:46.935 --> 03:49.229
‐ Well, looks like our
snowmobile went belly up.

03:49.229 --> 03:51.857
<i>‐ I need to get</i>
<i>a large piece of metal.</i>

03:51.857 --> 03:53.108
<i>That's a big knife.</i>

03:53.108 --> 03:54.401
<i>We've got the coil springs,</i>

03:54.401 --> 03:56.736
<i>which I know are</i>
<i>a great steel,</i>

03:56.736 --> 03:58.572
<i>but they're about</i>
<i>1/2 an inch thick.</i>

03:58.572 --> 04:01.158
So that's not enough steel
to work with.

04:01.158 --> 04:03.034
<i>I decided to go with the skis.</i>

04:03.034 --> 04:05.495
‐ Skis on this snowmobile
are high carbon.

04:05.495 --> 04:07.247
<i>They're 5160 spring steel.</i>

04:07.247 --> 04:09.708
<i>If it were me, I'd be going</i>
<i>for those skis for sure.</i>

04:09.708 --> 04:11.168
‐ And he's cutting it
at an angle.

04:11.168 --> 04:13.128
Is there a strategy to that?

04:13.128 --> 04:14.754
‐ Yeah, I think
he's preforming his tip.

04:14.754 --> 04:15.964
‐ Might as well.
It's a good idea.

04:15.964 --> 04:17.340
‐ I mean, I might even consider

04:17.340 --> 04:18.633
taking a big rectangular piece

04:18.633 --> 04:19.885
over to the Portaband

04:19.885 --> 04:21.428
and doing a rough profile.

04:21.428 --> 04:24.598
<i>‐ The skis are designed</i>
<i>to flex,</i>

04:24.598 --> 04:26.141
so I figure there's got to be
enough carbon in it

04:26.141 --> 04:29.644
to harden up and to maintain
a flexible spine.

04:29.644 --> 04:33.273
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:33.273 --> 04:35.567
‐ Kasey also has
one of the angle grinders,

04:35.567 --> 04:38.528
and he's just carving a piece
of that ski as well.

04:38.528 --> 04:40.363
‐ The temperature out here
is‐‐it's pretty cold.

04:40.363 --> 04:42.073
<i>But I'm from Montana</i>
<i>originally,</i>

04:42.073 --> 04:43.617
<i>so, you know,</i>
<i>I can suck it up.</i>

04:43.617 --> 04:45.744
[chuckles]
‐ When we talk about

04:45.744 --> 04:47.746
temperature extremes
in our forge,

04:47.746 --> 04:50.957
we're usually talking about
the high temperature extreme.

04:50.957 --> 04:54.252
Today it is 22 degrees.

04:54.252 --> 04:55.504
‐ It is cold,
and, you know,

04:55.504 --> 04:56.880
that's gonna play
in all sorts

04:56.880 --> 04:58.590
of different ways
with these smiths.

04:58.590 --> 05:00.133
<i>‐ I've made a kukri before,</i>

05:00.133 --> 05:01.885
<i>and it's actually</i>
<i>a really cool knife.</i>

05:01.885 --> 05:04.179
It's got some sex appeal to it
'cause it's got curves,

05:04.179 --> 05:06.473
<i>but I've never made</i>
<i>a through‐tang before,</i>

05:06.473 --> 05:09.142
so it's gonna be
a little bit of a challenge.

05:09.142 --> 05:12.187
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:12.187 --> 05:14.523
‐ Now Adam's cutting off
a hunk of ski.

05:14.523 --> 05:17.067
<i>‐ I feel fine working</i>
<i>in this environment.</i>

05:17.067 --> 05:19.653
<i>Right now at home,</i>
<i>it's colder than this</i>

05:19.653 --> 05:21.363
by, like, a lot.

05:21.363 --> 05:22.864
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:22.864 --> 05:26.201
<i>I cannot get this coal forge</i>

05:26.201 --> 05:29.037
going to save my life.

05:29.037 --> 05:31.373
‐ Why would the temperature
have anything to do

05:31.373 --> 05:34.042
with the ability
of the coal to burn?

05:34.042 --> 05:36.002
‐ It shouldn't.
It actually is a little bit

05:36.002 --> 05:39.047
beneficial because there's more
oxygen per cubic foot of air

05:39.047 --> 05:40.841
in cold air
than there is in hot air.

05:40.841 --> 05:43.718
‐ The mental aspect
of being in this cold

05:43.718 --> 05:45.929
has got to play a part in that.
‐ Certainly.

05:45.929 --> 05:49.099
<i>‐ I didn't come here to</i>
<i>struggle with starting a fire.</i>

05:49.099 --> 05:51.142
<i>I came here to struggle</i>
<i>over a knife.</i>

05:51.142 --> 05:53.061
<i>This is amateur hour.</i>

05:53.061 --> 05:54.062
Ridiculous!

05:54.062 --> 05:55.564
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:55.564 --> 05:57.732
<i>‐ All four smiths</i>
<i>have now harvested steel</i>

05:57.732 --> 06:00.026
<i>from the skis</i>
<i>of our snowmobile.</i>

06:00.026 --> 06:02.445
<i>‐ Grab my piece of steel,</i>
<i>take it to the anvil,</i>

06:02.445 --> 06:04.155
and then start focusing
on the forge.

06:04.155 --> 06:08.118
I, you know, have some
experience with coal forges.

06:08.118 --> 06:10.245
‐ Josh has
a pretty clean‐looking fire.

06:10.245 --> 06:12.372
‐ I'd love to see him build
that up a little bit more.

06:12.372 --> 06:14.749
Kind of want to have
that stack, that cave,

06:14.749 --> 06:17.794
where you've got a super hot
core in there.

06:17.794 --> 06:19.921
<i>‐ So with a coal forge,</i>
<i>just take care of it</i>

06:19.921 --> 06:22.299
<i>like if it was a baby,</i>
<i>a newborn.</i>

06:22.299 --> 06:24.175
Come on, baby.
Come on, baby.

06:24.175 --> 06:26.094
Do it for Daddy.
Do it for Daddy.

06:26.094 --> 06:29.347
<i>You have to really give</i>
<i>encouraging words</i>

06:29.347 --> 06:31.433
and really be very supportive.

06:31.433 --> 06:33.059
Now we're getting there.

06:33.059 --> 06:34.769
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:34.769 --> 06:36.104
‐ And what is that
that Ben's laying

06:36.104 --> 06:37.564
across the top of the fire?

06:37.564 --> 06:40.150
‐ That's the piece
of anvil‐heating steel.

06:40.150 --> 06:42.277
So heat that up,
lay it on the anvil,

06:42.277 --> 06:43.612
warm up that anvil.

06:43.612 --> 06:45.238
‐ I need to do my due diligence

06:45.238 --> 06:47.198
and make sure that
that anvil face

06:47.198 --> 06:49.242
is warm and not gonna be
sucking the heat out

06:49.242 --> 06:51.620
every time
I set my steel on it.

06:51.620 --> 06:53.622
‐ Keep it just living right
there on the edge of your coal

06:53.622 --> 06:55.081
so it's always warm.

06:55.081 --> 06:56.625
When you put your material
back in the coals,

06:56.625 --> 06:59.002
put that heating bar
back on the anvil.

06:59.002 --> 07:01.129
<i>‐ Overall I'm actually feeling</i>
<i>really good.</i>

07:01.129 --> 07:03.715
I'm able to hit it for
an appropriate amount of time

07:03.715 --> 07:05.800
<i>without getting tired,</i>
<i>put it back in the fire,</i>

07:05.800 --> 07:08.345
and by the time I'm ready
to swing again, it's hot.

07:08.345 --> 07:12.932
‐ Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed!

07:12.932 --> 07:15.602
<i>‐ I'm trying to crank my coal</i>
<i>forge with my right hand.</i>

07:15.602 --> 07:17.771
<i>I'm trying to use my MAPP gas</i>
<i>with my left hand</i>

07:17.771 --> 07:19.189
to heat up the face
of my anvil

07:19.189 --> 07:20.774
<i>so my steel</i>
<i>doesn't get cold.</i>

07:20.774 --> 07:22.400
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:22.400 --> 07:26.655
My strength is forging, so I'm
just trying to keep my heats

07:26.655 --> 07:28.448
<i>pretty quick so I can just</i>

07:28.448 --> 07:31.910
<i>forge a few times and then</i>
<i>back in the fire, pull it out,</i>

07:31.910 --> 07:33.870
hit it a few times,
back in the fire.

07:33.870 --> 07:35.664
‐ One of my concerns
watching Kasey,

07:35.664 --> 07:38.166
a lot of times, he's hammering
and it looks gray from here.

07:38.166 --> 07:41.294
‐ A lot of these smiths have
been going through today is,

07:41.294 --> 07:43.838
they pull it out of that forge
and it's glowing a nice orange,

07:43.838 --> 07:46.341
but it loses that color
so rapidly.

07:46.341 --> 07:48.551
<i>‐ I barely even moved</i>
<i>anything,</i>

07:48.551 --> 07:50.470
and I'm starting to freak out
a little bit.

07:50.470 --> 07:53.264
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:53.264 --> 07:56.101
‐ I finally get
my coal forge going.

07:56.101 --> 07:57.769
<i>Now it's time to start</i>

07:57.769 --> 08:00.647
hammering it into a kukri.

08:00.647 --> 08:02.190
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:02.190 --> 08:04.317
‐ Adam is actually forging
tang first.

08:04.317 --> 08:05.485
What do you think
of that strategy?

08:05.485 --> 08:06.653
‐ In a competition like this

08:06.653 --> 08:08.279
where the length
is a parameter,

08:08.279 --> 08:09.989
I usually start at the tip
and work my way back,

08:09.989 --> 08:11.574
'cause I can always cut in
a tang later;

08:11.574 --> 08:13.368
I can always add material
to the tang,

08:13.368 --> 08:14.703
mild steel or something.

08:14.703 --> 08:17.747
‐ When I first started
making blades,

08:17.747 --> 08:19.541
<i>my tangs were all over</i>
<i>the place.</i>

08:19.541 --> 08:22.168
<i>By doing a tang first,</i>
<i>I can pay greater attention</i>

08:22.168 --> 08:25.088
<i>to the detail of the tang.</i>

08:25.088 --> 08:26.506
I figure once I got that set,

08:26.506 --> 08:30.051
I just work my way
towards the tip.

08:30.051 --> 08:32.762
I can't seem to get
a good rhythm

08:32.762 --> 08:35.974
<i>with the heating,</i>
<i>the hammering.</i>

08:35.974 --> 08:38.351
I can't focus
on what I'm doing.

08:38.351 --> 08:41.563
<i>The clock is running down.</i>
<i>I need to finish this.</i>

08:41.563 --> 08:43.231
‐ He's got a long way to go.
‐ Yeah.

08:43.231 --> 08:47.110
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:47.110 --> 08:49.654
‐ If I hit my steel too cold,
the chances are

08:49.654 --> 08:52.032
that I'm gonna create
micro cracks,

08:52.032 --> 08:53.658
but I don't want to get it
too hot

08:53.658 --> 08:56.619
because I don't want to burn
the carbon out of it.

08:56.619 --> 08:58.830
‐ It's so bright out here,
you know,

08:58.830 --> 09:00.623
the sun reflecting
off the snow,

09:00.623 --> 09:04.377
that being able to see when
the steel is up in temperature,

09:04.377 --> 09:07.213
when it's getting a little bit
beyond temperature,

09:07.213 --> 09:10.258
we might see a lot of burning
steel in this environment.

09:10.258 --> 09:13.553
<i>‐ Shaping the blade,</i>
<i>the belly is going okay.</i>

09:13.553 --> 09:16.514
The curvature
that the kukri has

09:16.514 --> 09:18.475
<i>is not going so well.</i>

09:18.475 --> 09:22.062
It's not taking the shape
that I want it to take.

09:22.062 --> 09:24.355
Hopefully it works out.

09:24.355 --> 09:27.108
‐ Bladesmiths,
90 minutes has elapsed.

09:27.108 --> 09:28.943
That is half the time
in round one!

09:28.943 --> 09:31.571
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:31.571 --> 09:33.531
‐ I'm halfway through,
I've got a good knife shape,

09:33.531 --> 09:35.950
and it's time for me to start
working on the tang.

09:35.950 --> 09:38.244
‐ Ben is not slowing down
over there, man.

09:38.244 --> 09:39.662
If anything, he's hitting

09:39.662 --> 09:42.373
harder and faster
than he was before.

09:42.373 --> 09:43.917
‐ That's some stamina.

09:43.917 --> 09:45.794
I mean, he's hammering
a beautiful shape into that.

09:45.794 --> 09:47.212
‐ I'm putting my stuff
back in the fire.

09:47.212 --> 09:48.963
I'm trying to get that tang
heated up.

09:48.963 --> 09:51.257
<i>It's a lot of material to move</i>
<i>as quickly as I can.</i>

09:51.257 --> 09:53.802
<i>I need to get that</i>
<i>into a better shape.</i>

09:53.802 --> 09:56.971
I look away from the forge
a little bit too long...

09:56.971 --> 10:00.183
[bleep].

10:00.183 --> 10:02.519
‐ Ooh!
‐ And it's melting.

10:02.519 --> 10:05.688
‐ Ben lost a bit of his billet
from overheating.

10:05.688 --> 10:07.148
‐ At those elevated
temperatures,

10:07.148 --> 10:08.817
the grain is growing so fast,

10:08.817 --> 10:11.111
and it becomes brittle
even under the heat.

10:11.111 --> 10:12.654
‐ And I really look
at the thickness

10:12.654 --> 10:14.405
of what I have
and I realize

10:14.405 --> 10:16.199
I can draw this out;
I have enough material

10:16.199 --> 10:19.244
to actually make a more
appropriately sized tang

10:19.244 --> 10:21.162
with what I've got.

10:21.162 --> 10:26.042
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:26.042 --> 10:28.086
‐ Things are moving
a lot better now.

10:28.086 --> 10:30.755
<i>Definitely catching up</i>
<i>to the rest of the guys.</i>

10:30.755 --> 10:34.509
‐ That is an awesome swing
that Kasey has up there.

10:34.509 --> 10:36.177
‐ Yup, that's a farrier's
swing, man.

10:36.177 --> 10:38.263
‐ He's got that momentum going.
Wow.

10:38.263 --> 10:41.182
<i>‐ This part of the build</i>
<i>is fairly easy for me.</i>

10:41.182 --> 10:44.352
<i>I can usually see steel</i>
<i>and kind of know where I need</i>

10:44.352 --> 10:46.855
<i>to hit it to achieve</i>
<i>what I need to achieve.</i>

10:46.855 --> 10:48.690
<i>That just comes from being</i>
<i>a horseshoer.</i>

10:48.690 --> 10:51.401
You know, everything we do,
it revolves around learning

10:51.401 --> 10:54.571
what the anvil, tongs,
and hammer can do.

10:54.571 --> 10:56.030
‐ Bladesmiths, one hour!

10:56.030 --> 10:58.533
You have one hour remaining
to finish your work.

10:58.533 --> 11:00.076
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:00.076 --> 11:03.204
So Adam's got his blade laying
on his anvil right now.

11:03.204 --> 11:04.539
It's not in the fire.

11:04.539 --> 11:06.499
It looks like
his coals have died down.

11:06.499 --> 11:11.504
‐ With PTSD, my ability
to focus is limited.

11:11.504 --> 11:12.714
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:12.714 --> 11:14.299
<i>I can't concentrate.</i>

11:14.299 --> 11:16.217
‐ I'm a little bit worried
about Adam.

11:16.217 --> 11:23.266
<i>‐ I'm losing it.</i>
‐ What's going on?

11:23.266 --> 11:25.101
‐ I'm a little bit worried
about Adam.

11:25.101 --> 11:27.645
<i>‐ At this moment,</i>
<i>I'm out of it.</i>

11:27.645 --> 11:29.063
I'm lost in the sauce.

11:29.063 --> 11:31.232
<i>I can't get</i>
<i>what's in my head</i>

11:31.232 --> 11:33.693
<i>of what a kukri is supposed</i>
<i>to look like</i>

11:33.693 --> 11:37.071
and apply it to the piece
I'm working on.

11:37.071 --> 11:42.243
‐ Adam needs to just focus
on tip, belly, waist, tang.

11:42.243 --> 11:44.245
Make sure it hits
the parameters.

11:44.245 --> 11:45.747
Do your best work.

11:45.747 --> 11:49.626
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:49.626 --> 11:51.836
‐ I feel like
I'm falling behind.

11:51.836 --> 11:54.631
It's getting a little bit
frustrating.

11:54.631 --> 11:56.382
<i>The time is running out.</i>

11:56.382 --> 11:59.594
‐ If I were Josh, take his
metal right over to Kasey's

11:59.594 --> 12:01.262
and have him hammer it...
‐ [laughs]

12:01.262 --> 12:02.555
‐ And then take it away.
‐ Slip it in there.

12:02.555 --> 12:03.973
‐ Big blue.
‐ Yeah.

12:03.973 --> 12:05.475
<i>‐ There's no way</i>
<i>I'm gonna be able</i>

12:05.475 --> 12:07.268
to just, you know,
move so much material

12:07.268 --> 12:09.437
out of the tang,
so I'm gonna have to trim

12:09.437 --> 12:11.272
<i>some fat out of it.</i>

12:11.272 --> 12:13.107
‐ Looks like Josh
is gonna cut the tang.

12:13.107 --> 12:14.609
Smart move.

12:14.609 --> 12:17.320
<i>‐ I don't know if I'm ahead</i>
<i>or I'm behind.</i>

12:17.320 --> 12:19.781
<i>I just need to get</i>
<i>this kukri done.</i>

12:19.781 --> 12:20.907
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:20.907 --> 12:22.784
‐ 20 minutes, bladesmiths!

12:22.784 --> 12:24.077
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:24.077 --> 12:27.080
‐ I have to dig deep,
really deep.

12:27.080 --> 12:29.707
‐ And here we go.
Adam's back on his crank.

12:29.707 --> 12:31.417
He's getting that coal forge
going again.

12:31.417 --> 12:33.253
That's exactly
what he needs to do.

12:33.253 --> 12:35.964
<i>‐ I want to turn in</i>
<i>a completed blade.</i>

12:35.964 --> 12:38.967
I want to prove to myself
that I could do this.

12:38.967 --> 12:41.344
I really want to quit,
but I can't,

12:41.344 --> 12:44.305
'cause then PTSD won.
I can't let it.

12:44.305 --> 12:45.932
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:45.932 --> 12:47.850
‐ I wouldn't say I'm satisfied
with my blade.

12:47.850 --> 12:50.895
<i>Looking at it right now,</i>
<i>it's kind of fugly.</i>

12:50.895 --> 12:52.522
‐ No quenches out there.

12:52.522 --> 12:54.190
We don't even have heated oil.

12:54.190 --> 12:57.360
Now, that oil has got to be
right around, I don't know,

12:57.360 --> 12:59.320
20 degrees Fahrenheit.
‐ Yeah.

12:59.320 --> 13:02.323
‐ I want to make sure
that my oil is warm.

13:02.323 --> 13:04.158
<i>I don't want to have</i>
<i>a blade crack</i>

13:04.158 --> 13:05.785
<i>right in the middle of this.</i>

13:05.785 --> 13:07.370
‐ At least‐‐it's good to see
that Kasey's started

13:07.370 --> 13:09.831
warming up his oils.
He's getting there.

13:09.831 --> 13:12.583
‐ I'm getting frustrated not
being able to get an even heat

13:12.583 --> 13:15.044
throughout the entire part
of the knife itself.

13:15.044 --> 13:17.672
<i>There's only so much</i>
<i>you can do.</i>

13:17.672 --> 13:19.424
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:19.424 --> 13:20.842
‐ So we've got Kasey
in the quench.

13:20.842 --> 13:22.885
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:22.885 --> 13:26.180
‐ It's still pretty straight.
Didn't hear any pops or pings.

13:26.180 --> 13:28.016
‐ Kasey's blade
looks really good.

13:28.016 --> 13:32.145
‐ As long as it's not as crappy
as the rest of the guys',

13:32.145 --> 13:35.023
I should be okay.

13:35.023 --> 13:36.649
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:36.649 --> 13:39.694
‐ Ben is right there
with Kasey.

13:39.694 --> 13:42.697
They've been working nonstop
this entire round.

13:42.697 --> 13:44.240
‐ And their blades show that.

13:44.240 --> 13:46.117
I mean, they're good‐looking
profiles

13:46.117 --> 13:47.702
on both of those blades.

13:47.702 --> 13:52.373
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:52.373 --> 13:54.876
‐ Man, looks like Ben
just quenched over there.

13:54.876 --> 13:56.502
<i>‐ There's no warps.</i>

13:56.502 --> 13:58.087
<i>Everything looks as straight</i>
<i>as when I put it in.</i>

13:58.087 --> 13:59.547
<i>I'm happy</i>
<i>with the way it looks.</i>

13:59.547 --> 14:01.132
I think if I go into round two,

14:01.132 --> 14:02.967
<i>I'll definitely have</i>
<i>a good starting point.</i>

14:02.967 --> 14:04.886
Yeah, I think she's good.

14:04.886 --> 14:06.512
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:06.512 --> 14:08.056
<i>‐ I don't have the time</i>

14:08.056 --> 14:10.433
<i>to keep hitting this steel</i>
<i>anymore.</i>

14:10.433 --> 14:12.393
It's time to heat treat it.

14:12.393 --> 14:15.104
‐ The waist of that blade
near the tang

14:15.104 --> 14:17.482
is as wide as the belly of it.

14:17.482 --> 14:19.400
And he's got kind of this curve

14:19.400 --> 14:21.402
pounded into
the center section of it,

14:21.402 --> 14:23.237
but it's not a kukri shape.

14:23.237 --> 14:24.572
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:24.572 --> 14:27.241
‐ It looks straight.
It looks good.

14:27.241 --> 14:30.745
‐ It really is a unique shape
when we talk about the shape

14:30.745 --> 14:33.164
of a kukri.
‐ He's not looking.

14:33.164 --> 14:35.583
‐ I like how the spine
doesn't go straight

14:35.583 --> 14:38.294
and it has that angle in it.

14:38.294 --> 14:41.589
‐ I'm exhausted,
but I'm still smiling.

14:41.589 --> 14:43.216
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:43.216 --> 14:44.509
‐ Five minutes, bladesmiths.

14:44.509 --> 14:46.260
Five minutes remaining
in the round.

14:46.260 --> 14:48.262
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:48.262 --> 14:51.849
‐ I revert back to what I know,
which is heat steel,

14:51.849 --> 14:53.643
pound steel, repeat.

14:53.643 --> 14:57.688
And sure enough, I got
a blade shape out of it.

14:57.688 --> 14:59.398
‐ I just feel like Adam's blade

14:59.398 --> 15:01.567
is just the way wrong shape.

15:01.567 --> 15:04.737
‐ Yeah, but also, I don't think
Adam's blade is long enough.

15:04.737 --> 15:07.782
‐ Two minutes, bladesmiths!
Two minutes remaining!

15:07.782 --> 15:12.620
<i>‐ My blade is not looking</i>
<i>like a kukri,</i>

15:12.620 --> 15:15.289
but I still want to turn it in.

15:15.289 --> 15:16.457
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:16.457 --> 15:18.709
<i>I take my blade out of the oil</i>

15:18.709 --> 15:20.962
<i>and realize</i>

15:20.962 --> 15:23.756
my blade is 1/8 of an inch
short.

15:23.756 --> 15:25.758
‐ One minute, bladesmiths!

15:25.758 --> 15:29.470
‐ I don't have time
to reheat it or forge it out,

15:29.470 --> 15:32.598
so I do the next best thing.

15:32.598 --> 15:34.433
‐ Adam's hooking up
the welder.

15:34.433 --> 15:36.018
<i>‐ To get it long enough,</i>

15:36.018 --> 15:38.229
I just take a piece of rebar,

15:38.229 --> 15:40.982
weld it on, hack it off,
and that's my tip.

15:40.982 --> 15:43.568
‐ Adam added a half inch
to the tip of his knife.

15:43.568 --> 15:45.153
‐ To make the parameters.

15:45.153 --> 15:47.822
‐ Figure I can make it pretty
later.

15:47.822 --> 15:49.448
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:49.448 --> 15:51.617
‐ Five, four,

15:51.617 --> 15:54.203
three, two, one!

15:54.203 --> 15:55.955
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

15:55.955 --> 15:57.165
Drop your tools.

15:57.165 --> 16:00.418
This first round of forging
is over.

16:00.418 --> 16:03.004
‐ Good job, dude. [laughs]
‐ Yeah, man.

16:03.004 --> 16:04.589
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:04.589 --> 16:06.591
I really do not know
what the judges

16:06.591 --> 16:08.217
are gonna say
about my blade.

16:08.217 --> 16:10.636
<i>I hope that they see</i>
<i>what I see.</i>

16:10.636 --> 16:14.390
<i>I always hope for the best,</i>
<i>but at this point,</i>

16:14.390 --> 16:15.349
I don't know.

16:15.349 --> 16:18.186
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:18.186 --> 16:20.646
‐ Bladesmiths,
time has expired

16:20.646 --> 16:22.356
in our first round
of competition.

16:22.356 --> 16:25.109
This has been a tough day.
Each of you is to have made

16:25.109 --> 16:27.862
a kukri between 11 and 13
inches in length

16:27.862 --> 16:29.488
with a through‐tang.
Only three of you

16:29.488 --> 16:31.032
can move forward
in this competition.

16:31.032 --> 16:33.159
One of you has to leave
The Forge.

16:33.159 --> 16:35.745
Ben.

16:35.745 --> 16:37.205
<i>You're safe.</i>
<i>You're moving on</i>

16:37.205 --> 16:38.372
<i>to the next round</i>
<i>of competition.</i>

16:38.372 --> 16:39.540
Good job.

16:39.540 --> 16:41.125
Josh, you're up first.

16:41.125 --> 16:42.877
The judges want to take
a closer look at your work.

16:42.877 --> 16:46.172
Please present your blade
to the judges.

16:46.172 --> 16:47.798
<i>‐ All right, Josh,</i>
<i>first up,</i>

16:47.798 --> 16:50.760
the defining characteristics
are not here.

16:50.760 --> 16:52.637
This is not a kukri.

16:52.637 --> 16:53.846
This is a kukri.

16:53.846 --> 16:55.431
The back and the spine
you have,

16:55.431 --> 16:58.226
it comes to a point
so you can thrust with it.

16:58.226 --> 16:59.769
The belly and the waist
is there.

16:59.769 --> 17:03.648
You can make this a kukri
by following this shape.

17:03.648 --> 17:07.485
And luckily you have
enough steel to do that.

17:07.485 --> 17:08.819
‐ Kasey, you're up.

17:08.819 --> 17:11.155
Please present your blade
to the judges.

17:11.155 --> 17:13.282
‐ This profile is by far

17:13.282 --> 17:15.910
the closest to what
we think of as a kukri,

17:15.910 --> 17:18.246
but if you move forward
in the second round,

17:18.246 --> 17:20.248
you got to move
this choil back to here,

17:20.248 --> 17:21.582
because you need all that steel

17:21.582 --> 17:23.167
to be part
of your sharpened edge.

17:23.167 --> 17:25.002
‐ Okay.
‐ Adam, you're up.

17:25.002 --> 17:27.213
Please present your blade
to the judges.

17:27.213 --> 17:28.506
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:28.506 --> 17:30.258
‐ Adam, I saw a couple of times

17:30.258 --> 17:31.968
where that clock
got the better of you.

17:31.968 --> 17:35.304
But then I saw you reset
and continue,

17:35.304 --> 17:37.348
and I really
appreciate that.

17:37.348 --> 17:39.642
But unfortunately,
at the end of the day,

17:39.642 --> 17:40.893
that's not a kukri.

17:40.893 --> 17:42.228
And there's not
enough steel here

17:42.228 --> 17:44.063
to turn it into one
without a forge.

17:44.063 --> 17:46.148
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:46.148 --> 17:50.027
‐ Adam, unfortunately, your
blade doesn't make parameters

17:50.027 --> 17:51.696
because it's just not a kukri,

17:51.696 --> 17:53.406
and for that reason
we cannot have you

17:53.406 --> 17:55.449
move forward
in this competition.

17:55.449 --> 17:57.910
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:57.910 --> 17:59.912
‐ This experience
was enlightening.

17:59.912 --> 18:02.540
<i>Even in the midst of my</i>

18:02.540 --> 18:05.751
absolute mind brokenness,

18:05.751 --> 18:09.088
I still was able
to complete a blade.

18:09.088 --> 18:11.841
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:11.841 --> 18:13.509
‐ Bladesmiths,
congratulations.

18:13.509 --> 18:15.553
You guys battled through
some freezing temperatures

18:15.553 --> 18:18.055
to earn your spot here in the
second round of competition.

18:18.055 --> 18:19.724
Now that your blade's
been tempered,

18:19.724 --> 18:21.851
<i>it's time to make them</i>
<i>fully functional kukris</i>

18:21.851 --> 18:23.269
<i>by attaching handles,</i>
<i>bolsters,</i>

18:23.269 --> 18:25.187
<i>and butt caps</i>
<i>to your weapon.</i>

18:25.187 --> 18:27.064
Gentlemen, you'll have
three hours in this round

18:27.064 --> 18:29.150
in which to do this as well
as address the flaws and issues

18:29.150 --> 18:31.569
that were identified
in your blades.

18:31.569 --> 18:32.653
At the end of those
three hours,

18:32.653 --> 18:33.779
we'll be testing your blades

18:33.779 --> 18:35.323
for strength and durability

18:35.323 --> 18:37.199
in an ice block chop

18:37.199 --> 18:40.995
and for edge retention
in a climbing rope slice.

18:40.995 --> 18:43.956
Good luck.
Your three hours starts now.

18:43.956 --> 18:47.001
I want to talk right away
about Josh's blade.

18:47.001 --> 18:50.921
He doesn't have a kukri spine,
and he doesn't have a waist

18:50.921 --> 18:53.674
that is really clearly defined.

18:53.674 --> 18:55.843
‐ The quickest and easiest
thing for Josh to do

18:55.843 --> 18:57.845
is draw out the shape
of a kukri

18:57.845 --> 19:00.348
and grind all
the rest of it away.

19:00.348 --> 19:05.102
<i>‐ Apparently my knife</i>
<i>is too straight in the spine.</i>

19:05.102 --> 19:08.981
It does have a belly, but it
does not have the profile

19:08.981 --> 19:11.567
that they're looking for.

19:11.567 --> 19:13.361
<i>Keep grinding,</i>
<i>and all of a sudden,</i>

19:13.361 --> 19:14.987
<i>I see the light</i>
<i>at the end of the tunnel.</i>

19:14.987 --> 19:17.365
And finally I can see
a kukri coming out.

19:17.365 --> 19:20.242
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:20.242 --> 19:22.286
‐ Ben got pushed through
right away, but I'm looking

19:22.286 --> 19:24.121
at his blade,
and I think I see

19:24.121 --> 19:26.374
a little kicked warp
to his tang.

19:26.374 --> 19:27.875
<i>‐ I go and grab</i>
<i>some of the torches</i>

19:27.875 --> 19:29.669
<i>and I just go</i>
<i>start heating up.</i>

19:29.669 --> 19:33.089
<i>I'm trying to be very careful</i>
<i>to prevent it from</i>

19:33.089 --> 19:35.549
<i>ruining the heat treat</i>
<i>of the actual blade.</i>

19:35.549 --> 19:37.885
I get it hot and I just
kind of push on it a little bit

19:37.885 --> 19:41.347
until it's able to move over
in the direction that I want.

19:41.347 --> 19:44.350
Yeah, that'll do.

19:44.350 --> 19:46.769
<i>‐ I have to fix</i>
<i>my round one mistakes,</i>

19:46.769 --> 19:49.730
<i>which is moving</i>
<i>my choil back a little bit.</i>

19:49.730 --> 19:52.692
‐ He kind of put a choil
on there with a ricasso.

19:52.692 --> 19:54.402
He needs all the sharpened
blade he can get.

19:54.402 --> 19:56.153
He needs to grind
that choil out.

19:56.153 --> 19:58.239
<i>‐ This round two challenge</i>
<i>is definitely difficult.</i>

19:58.239 --> 20:01.075
<i>I'm definitely not the</i>
<i>greatest at fit and finish,</i>

20:01.075 --> 20:04.120
so this could be
a real challenge for me.

20:04.120 --> 20:07.581
‐ Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed!

20:07.581 --> 20:10.126
‐ Thank you, Will!
‐ You're welcome, Josh.

20:10.126 --> 20:12.753
‐ What I'm really concerned
right now is the tang.

20:12.753 --> 20:16.757
It seems like it's too up,
so the game plan now

20:16.757 --> 20:19.510
is just to get it
to be at least in line

20:19.510 --> 20:21.011
with the whole kukri.

20:21.011 --> 20:22.930
<i>I've been spending a lot</i>
<i>of time on this tang,</i>

20:22.930 --> 20:24.765
<i>and it's not working out.</i>

20:24.765 --> 20:28.561
‐ He cut his tang way down
and welded on some all thread.

20:28.561 --> 20:30.146
It's a really narrow piece
of all thread,

20:30.146 --> 20:32.022
so we'll see
how that holds up.

20:32.022 --> 20:34.567
‐ There's definitely
better ways to handle this,

20:34.567 --> 20:36.986
<i>but right now,</i>
<i>time is ticking</i>

20:36.986 --> 20:38.612
and I just needed to do it
this way.

20:38.612 --> 20:41.073
Live in the moment, brother.
Live in the moment.

20:41.073 --> 20:42.616
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:42.616 --> 20:44.243
‐ The kukri has to has to have
a through‐tang,

20:44.243 --> 20:45.953
which is gonna be a bit
of a challenge.

20:45.953 --> 20:47.705
<i>At this point, I know</i>
<i>the clock's ticking down,</i>

20:47.705 --> 20:49.874
<i>and I'm going to do</i>
<i>a burn‐through.</i>

20:49.874 --> 20:51.459
<i>It's how it was done</i>
<i>traditionally.</i>

20:51.459 --> 20:53.127
<i>It's how I usually do it.</i>

20:53.127 --> 20:54.795
‐ I've never been a fan
of the burn‐through.

20:54.795 --> 20:57.381
Even if you get the tang
to go through your handle,

20:57.381 --> 20:59.592
you now have a completely
charred inside,

20:59.592 --> 21:01.844
so you're left with a liner
on the inside of that hole

21:01.844 --> 21:03.888
that's not strong material.

21:03.888 --> 21:06.098
<i>‐ There are few alternatives</i>
<i>to a burn‐through.</i>

21:06.098 --> 21:09.143
I could take scales
and try and chisel out

21:09.143 --> 21:11.353
<i>the tang shape and then</i>
<i>put them together,</i>

21:11.353 --> 21:12.813
<i>but that's really</i>
<i>time‐intensive,</i>

21:12.813 --> 21:14.940
and I don't see
any good materials

21:14.940 --> 21:16.484
<i>to do that.</i>

21:16.484 --> 21:18.486
I just go millimeter
by millimeter, inch by inch,

21:18.486 --> 21:19.820
but time is running out.

21:19.820 --> 21:22.531
‐ Bladesmiths,
90 minutes has elapsed.

21:22.531 --> 21:24.992
‐ And then it occurs to me,
I have two hands.

21:24.992 --> 21:26.410
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:26.410 --> 21:29.163
<i>That makes it go</i>
<i>quite a bit quicker.</i>

21:29.163 --> 21:31.499
‐ Ben, he's got two
MAPP gas torches going

21:31.499 --> 21:33.000
against the tang
of this blade,

21:33.000 --> 21:35.127
and he's trying
to force that burn‐through.

21:35.127 --> 21:39.507
‐ Eventually it starts to go
down, and it fits awesome.

21:39.507 --> 21:40.883
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:40.883 --> 21:42.051
<i>‐ The bolster</i>
<i>is the foundation</i>

21:42.051 --> 21:43.385
<i>of your entire handle.</i>

21:43.385 --> 21:45.012
Basically,
if this doesn't fit right,

21:45.012 --> 21:46.180
the rest of my handle won't.

21:46.180 --> 21:48.349
<i>So I'm trying to take as much</i>

21:48.349 --> 21:49.809
<i>time as I can to get that</i>

21:49.809 --> 21:51.769
<i>as perfect as possible.</i>

21:51.769 --> 21:54.355
‐ Bladesmiths,
two hours has elapsed.

21:54.355 --> 21:55.815
<i>‐ Finally I get the bolster</i>
<i>to fit,</i>

21:55.815 --> 21:57.942
and now it's time
for the handle.

21:57.942 --> 22:00.152
<i>I either have to try</i>
<i>drilling through</i>

22:00.152 --> 22:01.654
<i>or try to do a burn‐in.</i>

22:01.654 --> 22:04.448
I figure, "You know what?
Let's try for the burn‐in."

22:04.448 --> 22:05.783
‐ Whoo!
Oh, my God!

22:05.783 --> 22:07.368
‐ That's gonna take too long!

22:07.368 --> 22:11.080
This is a monkey‐see,
monkey‐do disaster.

22:11.080 --> 22:14.291
<i>‐ I start burning it on,</i>
<i>and it's just taking forever.</i>

22:14.291 --> 22:17.419
‐ Kasey has maybe made a huge
tactical error by opting

22:17.419 --> 22:19.547
for the burn‐through.
‐ Ugh.

22:19.547 --> 22:21.465
Definitely feeling the pressure
at this moment.

22:21.465 --> 22:24.927
‐ He's trying to force that
burn‐through, and in the past,

22:24.927 --> 22:28.305
we've seen snaps; we've seen
failures in the actual testing

22:28.305 --> 22:30.140
because
of the structural integrity.

22:30.140 --> 22:31.433
‐ I hate this burn‐in.

22:31.433 --> 22:32.935
It's the stupidest decision
I made.

22:32.935 --> 22:34.562
‐ Give up on the burn‐through.

22:34.562 --> 22:35.729
Give up on the burn‐through.

22:35.729 --> 22:36.856
<i>‐ If I don't get this done,</i>

22:36.856 --> 22:41.110
<i>I won't have a knife.</i>

22:41.110 --> 22:42.236
<i>‐ I start burning it on,</i>

22:42.236 --> 22:43.863
<i>and it's just taking forever.</i>

22:43.863 --> 22:46.198
Definitely feeling the pressure
at this moment.

22:46.198 --> 22:47.867
‐ There comes a point
where a smith

22:47.867 --> 22:50.202
keeps butting his head
against the wall.

22:50.202 --> 22:51.537
You got to stop that.

22:51.537 --> 22:53.539
<i>‐ It's just not burning</i>
<i>fast enough,</i>

22:53.539 --> 22:55.291
so I decide to just, you know,

22:55.291 --> 22:56.625
go for a Hail Mary
and just start

22:56.625 --> 22:58.335
<i>drilling through</i>
<i>the other side.</i>

22:58.335 --> 23:01.046
Hopefully I'll meet
in the middle somewhere.

23:01.046 --> 23:03.757
‐ 15 minutes, bladesmiths!

23:03.757 --> 23:06.385
‐ I have a handle complete,
so all I need to do now

23:06.385 --> 23:08.053
is shape the handle.

23:08.053 --> 23:10.681
<i>Everything looks good,</i>
<i>and all of a sudden,</i>

23:10.681 --> 23:12.683
I see a hole.

23:12.683 --> 23:14.226
[bleep].

23:14.226 --> 23:16.729
If I leave this hole
and maybe one of the judges

23:16.729 --> 23:19.023
is gonna say,
"This is not safe."

23:19.023 --> 23:21.734
<i>So I figure, I'm gonna go</i>
<i>and grab just a piece</i>

23:21.734 --> 23:24.069
<i>of paper towel</i>
<i>and just stuff it in there.</i>

23:24.069 --> 23:26.989
Just stuff it.
‐ Here's a guy that knows how

23:26.989 --> 23:28.073
to work around obstacles.

23:28.073 --> 23:30.409
I love him!
[laughs]

23:30.409 --> 23:33.162
‐ I think I'm safe.
Question mark?

23:33.162 --> 23:36.916
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:36.916 --> 23:38.876
‐ It takes a lot of heat
to get the end of the tang

23:38.876 --> 23:41.086
soft enough
so that I can peen it over.

23:41.086 --> 23:42.588
‐ The guard's bouncing around

23:42.588 --> 23:44.590
'cause he's got too much tang
sticking out.

23:44.590 --> 23:47.092
‐ As I'm heating it up,
it's starting to soften

23:47.092 --> 23:49.762
<i>the epoxy</i>
<i>at the end of the tang.</i>

23:49.762 --> 23:51.096
<i>Epoxy breaks down under heat,</i>

23:51.096 --> 23:53.223
<i>and if it doesn't properly</i>
<i>cure up,</i>

23:53.223 --> 23:56.143
<i>there may be some handle</i>
<i>wobble after the ice chop.</i>

23:56.143 --> 23:58.604
Right now, it's looking right,
so can't complain.

23:58.604 --> 24:00.272
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:00.272 --> 24:02.441
‐ Five minutes, bladesmiths!

24:02.441 --> 24:03.859
‐ Oh, come on.
Fit.

24:03.859 --> 24:05.611
I can't get
my handle material on there.

24:05.611 --> 24:10.240
‐ The guy who had the best
blade coming out of round one

24:10.240 --> 24:11.825
doesn't have a handle on it!

24:11.825 --> 24:14.203
<i>‐ I don't even have time</i>
<i>for five‐minute epoxy.</i>

24:14.203 --> 24:16.538
It's gonna have to be
a peened‐on handle.

24:16.538 --> 24:18.457
‐ He's got a 1/2 inch,
almost 3/4 of an inch

24:18.457 --> 24:19.792
of tang sticking out.
‐ Fold it over.

24:19.792 --> 24:21.293
‐ It's so long.
‐ Fold it over flat.

24:21.293 --> 24:22.628
‐ Just knock it over, Dave?

24:22.628 --> 24:24.254
‐ Heat it up.
Bend it over flat.

24:24.254 --> 24:26.840
‐ They can't test it
unless it's a finished blade,

24:26.840 --> 24:28.968
so see where it goes.

24:28.968 --> 24:31.971
‐ Five, four, three,

24:31.971 --> 24:33.973
two, one!

24:33.973 --> 24:35.516
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

24:35.516 --> 24:36.809
Drop your tools.

24:36.809 --> 24:40.354
This second round
of competition is over.

24:40.354 --> 24:43.315
‐ Good job, bud.

24:43.315 --> 24:44.692
I pretty much realized
that my knife

24:44.692 --> 24:46.819
<i>is the worst one</i>
<i>out there.</i>

24:46.819 --> 24:49.113
<i>It's a piece of crap,</i>
<i>but if for some reason</i>

24:49.113 --> 24:50.531
<i>one of the other blades</i>

24:50.531 --> 24:52.157
doesn't meet the parameters
in some way,

24:52.157 --> 24:53.826
<i>then I still have a shot.</i>

24:53.826 --> 24:56.161
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:56.161 --> 24:58.998
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to the ice block chop.

24:58.998 --> 25:00.499
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:00.499 --> 25:02.209
To test the strength
and durability of your blades

25:02.209 --> 25:03.836
as well as the overall
construction of your kukris,

25:03.836 --> 25:05.796
I will be bashing them
mercilessly

25:05.796 --> 25:07.047
into these blocks of ice.

25:07.047 --> 25:08.298
Ben, you're up first.

25:08.298 --> 25:09.675
You ready for this?
‐ We'll see.

25:09.675 --> 25:11.010
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:11.010 --> 25:12.678
<i>I'm concerned</i>
<i>about the ice chop</i>

25:12.678 --> 25:14.555
<i>because it's</i>
<i>a really, really hard shock</i>

25:14.555 --> 25:16.015
<i>on any blade.</i>

25:16.015 --> 25:17.516
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:17.516 --> 25:18.517
The handle is what I'm really

25:18.517 --> 25:20.102
<i>most concerned about.</i>

25:20.102 --> 25:27.234
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:37.036 --> 25:38.537
[laughter]

25:38.537 --> 25:40.539
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:40.539 --> 25:42.750
‐ Well, Ben, the first thing
I feel

25:42.750 --> 25:44.376
when I pick this knife up
is its weight.

25:44.376 --> 25:46.253
This thing is really heavy.

25:46.253 --> 25:48.881
The handle, it's comfortable.

25:48.881 --> 25:50.758
I could hold on to it.
But it is small.

25:50.758 --> 25:53.135
The edge you put on there
held up really well on the ice.

25:53.135 --> 25:56.555
I mean, there's no damage
to your edge at all.

25:56.555 --> 25:58.557
Well done.
‐ Thank you, sir.

25:58.557 --> 26:00.225
‐ Josh, you're up next.
How you feeling?

26:00.225 --> 26:03.228
‐ Nervous, but go crazy.

26:03.228 --> 26:04.396
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:04.396 --> 26:07.066
<i>Ben went first.</i>
<i>He did amazing.</i>

26:07.066 --> 26:10.319
His chopper destroyed that ice,

26:10.319 --> 26:13.572
so now I'm really
feeling nervous.

26:13.572 --> 26:20.621
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:35.010 --> 26:36.845
‐ Well, Josh,
first things first.

26:36.845 --> 26:39.056
Your blade has a kukri shape
and profile.

26:39.056 --> 26:41.100
It is still very heavy.

26:41.100 --> 26:43.602
Swinging this all day
would be really tiring.

26:43.602 --> 26:46.105
Moving on to your handle,
it's on the small side,

26:46.105 --> 26:47.689
but it's comfortable.

26:47.689 --> 26:49.858
The one thing that gives me
a lot of issue, though,

26:49.858 --> 26:52.111
is where you completely
ground through,

26:52.111 --> 26:54.780
exposing your tang hole there.

26:54.780 --> 26:57.783
[laughing]
And then filled it with‐‐

26:57.783 --> 26:59.785
with paper towel.
It certainly at least

26:59.785 --> 27:02.955
filled the void and didn't
really hurt my finger, so...

27:02.955 --> 27:04.957
an interesting work‐around.
Well done.

27:04.957 --> 27:07.334
‐ Thank you very much.
‐ Kasey.

27:07.334 --> 27:08.961
You're up, man.
How you feeling?

27:08.961 --> 27:10.629
‐ Not too great, but‐‐
[laughs]

27:10.629 --> 27:12.631
‐ All right, well,
we're gonna do it anyway.

27:12.631 --> 27:13.632
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:13.632 --> 27:15.259
<i>‐ The handle sucks.</i>

27:15.259 --> 27:16.468
<i>I wish I had a little bit</i>
<i>more time</i>

27:16.468 --> 27:19.179
<i>to clean up all my edges.</i>

27:19.179 --> 27:20.931
<i>I'm just hoping</i>
<i>that it just doesn't</i>

27:20.931 --> 27:22.599
<i>hurt one of the judges.</i>

27:22.599 --> 27:25.310
This is crazy.

27:25.310 --> 27:32.401
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:45.914 --> 27:50.043
‐ This is a square,
sharp cornered block,

27:50.043 --> 27:53.672
and it bit into my hand
like there's no tomorrow.

27:53.672 --> 27:56.216
But your blade held up,
it's all in one piece,

27:56.216 --> 27:59.011
so really good job
on the steel.

27:59.011 --> 28:01.722
But this handle
is just not there.

28:01.722 --> 28:03.265
‐ Thank you.

28:03.265 --> 28:07.144
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:07.144 --> 28:08.562
‐ All right, bladesmiths.

28:08.562 --> 28:10.022
Welcome to the sharpness test,

28:10.022 --> 28:12.357
the climbing rope slice.

28:12.357 --> 28:15.861
A sharp blade should cut easily
through these ropes.

28:15.861 --> 28:18.363
A dull one would just cut
the exterior or, worse,

28:18.363 --> 28:20.032
do nothing at all.
Ben, you're up first.

28:20.032 --> 28:22.367
You ready?
‐ Let's do it.

28:22.367 --> 28:25.245
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:25.245 --> 28:26.872
‐ Climbing rope
is multilayered.

28:26.872 --> 28:28.206
There's an outer sheath,
an inner sheath.

28:28.206 --> 28:30.250
<i>There's a lot to cut through.</i>

28:30.250 --> 28:32.294
<i>I gave my blade</i>
<i>a really obtuse grind</i>

28:32.294 --> 28:34.421
<i>to make sure it would</i>
<i>stay true in the ice chop.</i>

28:34.421 --> 28:36.214
<i>I'm hoping that blade</i>
<i>isn't too obtuse</i>

28:36.214 --> 28:39.217
so that it won't cut easily
through the rope.

28:39.217 --> 28:46.391
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:56.693 --> 28:58.904
‐ All right, Ben.
First up, when you pick up

28:58.904 --> 29:01.406
your blade,
it's heavy.

29:01.406 --> 29:04.576
Choppers are forward heavy,
but your blade is just heavy.

29:04.576 --> 29:08.080
Now, the handle construction
here is smooth and comfortable.

29:08.080 --> 29:10.457
But because it's so smooth
and the weight of your blade,

29:10.457 --> 29:12.918
it's almost like it wants
to fly away from my hand.

29:12.918 --> 29:16.797
But your edge is sharp,
and for this test,

29:16.797 --> 29:18.090
it will cut.

29:18.090 --> 29:19.925
‐ Glad to hear it.
Thank you.

29:19.925 --> 29:22.469
‐ All right, Josh, your turn.
You ready for this?

29:22.469 --> 29:24.012
‐ Uh, let's go for it.

29:24.012 --> 29:26.723
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:26.723 --> 29:28.433
I made it through the ice.

29:28.433 --> 29:31.853
<i>Now I just need to cut</i>
<i>some rope.</i>

29:31.853 --> 29:38.318
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:46.076 --> 29:48.620
‐ All right, Josh, let's talk
about your kukri here.

29:48.620 --> 29:51.123
On the first slice, you did
cut through the outer layer.

29:51.123 --> 29:52.958
It didn't cut
all the way through.

29:52.958 --> 29:55.669
On the second slices, it cut
cleanly once you can adjust

29:55.669 --> 29:57.546
to the weight and I can tell
exactly where

29:57.546 --> 29:59.506
the cutting edge
of this blade is.

29:59.506 --> 30:01.967
And for this test, sir,
it will cut.

30:01.967 --> 30:03.635
‐ Thank you very much.

30:03.635 --> 30:06.888
‐ All right, Kasey, it's time.

30:06.888 --> 30:08.640
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:08.640 --> 30:10.642
<i>‐ I'm just feeling,</i>
<i>you know, disappointed</i>

30:10.642 --> 30:12.561
because I already know
what the outcome is gonna be.

30:12.561 --> 30:14.312
<i>It's not a finished blade.</i>

30:14.312 --> 30:16.148
<i>My wife loves Doug Marcaida,</i>

30:16.148 --> 30:18.191
and if my knife hurts his hand,

30:18.191 --> 30:20.318
I have no idea where
I'm gonna be sleeping.

30:20.318 --> 30:21.486
[chuckles]

30:21.486 --> 30:28.618
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:36.918 --> 30:39.546
‐ Kasey, we really appreciate
you coming in

30:39.546 --> 30:41.923
and competing in extreme
of circumstances.

30:41.923 --> 30:45.177
You have the best hammer swing
right there.

30:45.177 --> 30:48.013
But at the end of the day,
that's not really a handle.

30:48.013 --> 30:49.681
It's blocky.
When you grab on to it,

30:49.681 --> 30:52.350
you hurt me, you hurt Ben,
and if you don't have

30:52.350 --> 30:54.936
an edge on your knife,
it's not a knife.

30:54.936 --> 30:59.691
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:59.691 --> 31:02.069
‐ Gentlemen, these tests
are all performance‐based,

31:02.069 --> 31:04.696
and, Kasey, your blade
just doesn't make the cut.

31:04.696 --> 31:06.865
There's no need for the judges
to deliberate.

31:06.865 --> 31:08.533
I have to dismiss you
from The Forge.

31:08.533 --> 31:09.951
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:09.951 --> 31:11.369
<i>‐ First thing I do</i>
<i>when I get home is,</i>

31:11.369 --> 31:12.621
I'm gonna go out
in the shop

31:12.621 --> 31:13.705
and I'm gonna make
a frickin' kukri

31:13.705 --> 31:15.040
<i>with a through‐tang,</i>

31:15.040 --> 31:16.541
<i>and I'm gonna take</i>
<i>a picture of it</i>

31:16.541 --> 31:17.793
and I'm gonna send it
to all the judges.

31:17.793 --> 31:19.377
[chuckles]
Good job, bud.

31:19.377 --> 31:20.879
‐ A pleasure.
<i>‐ To all the people out there</i>

31:20.879 --> 31:22.881
who look at the competitors
and they go,

31:22.881 --> 31:25.092
"Oh, man, you could have
done it so much better,"

31:25.092 --> 31:26.551
<i>put your money</i>
<i>where your mouth is.</i>

31:26.551 --> 31:28.136
<i>Come out here and try it,</i>

31:28.136 --> 31:29.888
because it is a lot harder
than it looks.

31:29.888 --> 31:32.390
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:32.390 --> 31:34.726
‐ Josh, Ben, congratulations.

31:34.726 --> 31:36.561
You guys have made it
to the final round

31:36.561 --> 31:38.271
of this competition.
Now we're sending you back

31:38.271 --> 31:40.065
to your home forges
to re‐create

31:40.065 --> 31:41.733
this iconic weapon
from history.

31:41.733 --> 31:44.611
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:44.611 --> 31:46.988
The Ram Dao.

31:46.988 --> 31:49.241
‐ Whoo.

31:49.241 --> 31:51.618
<i>‐ The Ram Dao is a sacrificial</i>
<i>sword that descends</i>

31:51.618 --> 31:55.247
<i>from the weapons of India's</i>
<i>legendary Rajput warriors.</i>

31:55.247 --> 31:58.083
<i>Its broad, heavy blade flares</i>
<i>to an ax‐like projection</i>

31:58.083 --> 32:00.252
<i>which is ideally suited</i>
<i>to the ritual beheading</i>

32:00.252 --> 32:03.630
<i>of large animals</i>
<i>such as buffalo and goats.</i>

32:03.630 --> 32:06.299
<i>These sacrifices were made</i>
<i>to the Hindu goddess of death,</i>

32:06.299 --> 32:08.927
<i>Kali, whose symbolic eye</i>
<i>is often etched</i>

32:08.927 --> 32:10.387
<i>on the flared end of the blade</i>

32:10.387 --> 32:12.389
<i>so she can watch over</i>
<i>the ceremony.</i>

32:12.389 --> 32:16.101
<i>The eye of Kali can be seen</i>
<i>on the Ram Dao wielded by Zodd</i>

32:16.101 --> 32:19.271
<i>in the comic series</i>
<i>"Berserk."</i>

32:19.271 --> 32:20.647
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:20.647 --> 32:22.607
Josh, Ben,
your final challenge

32:22.607 --> 32:24.151
is to forge a Ram Dao.

32:24.151 --> 32:26.319
It must be an effective
and deadly version

32:26.319 --> 32:27.946
of the weapon
that you see here.

32:27.946 --> 32:29.531
Just make sure
that your blades fall

32:29.531 --> 32:30.949
within the following
parameters.

32:30.949 --> 32:32.784
Now, length of the blade
must be between

32:32.784 --> 32:34.703
20 and 23 inches
in length.

32:34.703 --> 32:37.789
It must have a finial ball,
a decorative eye of Kali,

32:37.789 --> 32:39.374
a demon buffalo hat,

32:39.374 --> 32:41.543
as well as a disk pommel.

32:41.543 --> 32:43.128
Failure to meet a single one
of our parameters

32:43.128 --> 32:45.672
is grounds for immediate
dismissal from this forge

32:45.672 --> 32:48.133
with no deliberation.

32:48.133 --> 32:50.635
‐ I feel excited about it
because it's something

32:50.635 --> 32:53.638
<i>that I never,</i>
<i>ever done before.</i>

32:53.638 --> 32:56.641
So let's do it.

32:56.641 --> 32:58.143
‐ You'll have four days
at your home forges

32:58.143 --> 32:59.811
in which to complete
this challenge.

32:59.811 --> 33:02.105
At the end of those four days,
you'll return and present

33:02.105 --> 33:04.316
your weapons to our panel
of expert judges,

33:04.316 --> 33:06.151
and after they've
thoroughly tested them,

33:06.151 --> 33:08.278
they'll declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

33:08.278 --> 33:10.864
who walks out of here
with a check for ten grand.

33:10.864 --> 33:13.658
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in four days.

33:13.658 --> 33:19.331
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:19.331 --> 33:23.501
‐ First thing I'm trying to do
is have a very good visual

33:23.501 --> 33:25.253
of what I'm gonna
be aiming for.

33:25.253 --> 33:28.840
Also, I need to concentrate
on the finial right here.

33:28.840 --> 33:30.842
That's gonna be something
that I need to keep my eye on,

33:30.842 --> 33:32.636
and it's gonna be
a challenge.

33:32.636 --> 33:34.638
So this is the piece
that I'm gonna be using.

33:34.638 --> 33:36.890
It's 5160 steel.

33:36.890 --> 33:40.393
<i>I never really have shaped</i>
<i>something like this before,</i>

33:40.393 --> 33:43.521
<i>so I feel that the easiest way</i>
<i>for me to shape</i>

33:43.521 --> 33:46.358
<i>that curve is just to start</i>
<i>using the anvil</i>

33:46.358 --> 33:49.527
<i>as a hammer,</i>
<i>and it actually worked.</i>

33:49.527 --> 33:50.987
<i>The process is going great.</i>

33:50.987 --> 33:54.199
<i>So far, we got the basic</i>
<i>profile done.</i>

33:54.199 --> 33:57.035
Day one is over.
Let's go have dinner.

33:57.035 --> 34:01.665
This is <i>mi abuelita,</i>
the matriarch of the family.

34:01.665 --> 34:04.542
I'm tired, and I'm ready
to stuff my face up

34:04.542 --> 34:07.212
<i>with a good dinner.</i>
‐ [praying in Spanish]

34:07.212 --> 34:09.047
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:09.047 --> 34:10.382
<i>‐ I'm back to my home forge.</i>

34:10.382 --> 34:12.759
<i>It is about five degrees</i>
<i>right now.</i>

34:12.759 --> 34:14.719
<i>Spring steel</i>
<i>is a great material</i>

34:14.719 --> 34:16.888
<i>for something like this.</i>
<i>It's gonna take a lot of abuse</i>

34:16.888 --> 34:18.890
<i>and be able to flex</i>
<i>over and over again.</i>

34:18.890 --> 34:20.433
So what I'm gonna try
and do first

34:20.433 --> 34:22.102
is drawing out the tang.

34:22.102 --> 34:24.396
I'm gonna do a through‐tang,
so it's gonna need to be long

34:24.396 --> 34:26.314
<i>but also thicker</i>
<i>than the rest of the blade</i>

34:26.314 --> 34:28.733
<i>to give it strength.</i>
<i>It's a big piece of steel,</i>

34:28.733 --> 34:31.069
<i>but I'll cut it.</i>

34:31.069 --> 34:33.280
Oh, here it goes.

34:33.280 --> 34:35.240
[clanging]
Boom!

34:35.240 --> 34:36.783
<i>The sun is setting,</i>
<i>it's starting to get</i>

34:36.783 --> 34:38.743
<i>even colder</i>
<i>than it already was,</i>

34:38.743 --> 34:42.914
<i>so I'm about to probably</i>
<i>call it a night.</i>

34:42.914 --> 34:45.417
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:45.417 --> 34:49.254
‐ All right, so everything
ready for quenching.

34:49.254 --> 34:52.966
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:52.966 --> 34:56.886
<i>The heat treatment</i>
<i>is the soul of the knife.</i>

34:56.886 --> 35:00.265
This has to go well,
and I'm just noticing

35:00.265 --> 35:02.976
<i>a slight curve.</i>

35:02.976 --> 35:07.939
It's not going away.

35:07.939 --> 35:09.107
‐ I'm not gonna lose
because of a warp.

35:09.107 --> 35:10.817
I'm gonna go ahead
and requench.

35:10.817 --> 35:12.777
<i>If it doesn't go well,</i>
<i>that's gonna push me</i>

35:12.777 --> 35:16.114
<i>to start all over again.</i>

35:16.114 --> 35:18.783
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

35:18.783 --> 35:20.452
Hopefully it worked.

35:20.452 --> 35:24.789
Yeah.
Yeah, it's beautiful!

35:24.789 --> 35:26.291
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:26.291 --> 35:28.918
<i>‐ I have it hot cut.</i>
<i>Now I need to add</i>

35:28.918 --> 35:32.839
<i>the sweep to it, which is</i>
<i>gonna be challenging.</i>

35:32.839 --> 35:36.468
I almost forgot about
the decorative finial

35:36.468 --> 35:37.844
at the top.

35:37.844 --> 35:39.262
That's kind of one of
the things about being

35:39.262 --> 35:41.806
a ceremonial,
sacrificial sword.

35:41.806 --> 35:43.850
<i>There's a lot of stuff on it</i>
<i>that's decorative</i>

35:43.850 --> 35:47.103
<i>that serves no purpose</i>
<i>other than for religious use,</i>

35:47.103 --> 35:49.147
but I forget about it
'cause I'm not used

35:49.147 --> 35:51.524
to making this stuff.

35:51.524 --> 35:53.568
<i>Okay, the blade looks good.</i>

35:53.568 --> 35:55.278
<i>I've got enough material</i>
<i>to work with,</i>

35:55.278 --> 35:59.658
so I'm gonna go take it
downstairs, start grinding.

35:59.658 --> 36:03.328
This is my homemade
belt grinder,

36:03.328 --> 36:05.580
<i>and this is how</i>
<i>I have to start this thing.</i>

36:05.580 --> 36:07.832
[whirring]

36:07.832 --> 36:13.922
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:15.006 --> 36:17.592
<i>It's straight.</i>
<i>I have my bevels ground in.</i>

36:17.592 --> 36:20.178
<i>It is the shape</i>
<i>it needs to be.</i>

36:20.178 --> 36:23.014
I'm looking to heat treat
tonight.

36:23.014 --> 36:25.475
<i>‐ The start of day four</i>
<i>is here.</i>

36:25.475 --> 36:28.353
I'm gonna go ahead and start
working on the handle.

36:28.353 --> 36:31.189
<i>Ideally, what I want</i>
<i>is to have a handle</i>

36:31.189 --> 36:33.024
<i>not just nice‐looking,</i>
<i>beautiful</i>

36:33.024 --> 36:36.111
<i>but also something</i>
<i>that is comfortable.</i>

36:36.111 --> 36:38.530
So I need to have a handle
that has a grip to it,

36:38.530 --> 36:42.200
that it doesn't feel like
it's gonna fly off the hand.

36:42.200 --> 36:43.910
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:43.910 --> 36:46.413
<i>I've never done finial.</i>

36:46.413 --> 36:48.957
This was definitely
very challenging.

36:48.957 --> 36:52.877
<i>I went with</i>
<i>a diamond‐looking piece.</i>

36:52.877 --> 36:55.130
It's different.

36:55.130 --> 36:57.924
<i>I need to really</i>
<i>make this blade pop,</i>

36:57.924 --> 37:00.176
<i>so besides the eye</i>
<i>and the crown</i>

37:00.176 --> 37:02.721
I decide to add extra edging
into it.

37:02.721 --> 37:05.598
<i>But no matter how beautiful</i>
<i>the blade is,</i>

37:05.598 --> 37:08.935
<i>if you miss one</i>
<i>of the parameters,</i>

37:08.935 --> 37:10.895
you're out
of the competition.

37:10.895 --> 37:13.106
<i>‐ It's day four.</i>

37:13.106 --> 37:16.234
<i>There's a bit of a warp</i>
<i>that happened</i>

37:16.234 --> 37:18.737
<i>during the tempering</i>
<i>of the spine.</i>

37:18.737 --> 37:20.613
<i>And I don't have enough time</i>
<i>to requench.</i>

37:20.613 --> 37:23.241
<i>I have too much</i>
<i>other stuff to do.</i>

37:23.241 --> 37:27.412
<i>But I can still make</i>
<i>this blade look the part</i>

37:27.412 --> 37:29.581
<i>and I can still make it</i>
<i>perform really, really well.</i>

37:29.581 --> 37:31.916
<i>So that's my goal for today.</i>

37:31.916 --> 37:39.090
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:42.343 --> 37:45.096
<i>I'm just getting to work</i>
<i>on the finial.</i>

37:45.096 --> 37:47.307
<i>It doesn't have to look like</i>
<i>anything in particular.</i>

37:47.307 --> 37:49.601
<i>It's just kind of a knob</i>
<i>at the end.</i>

37:49.601 --> 37:51.394
<i>I don't do a whole lot</i>
<i>of engraving,</i>

37:51.394 --> 37:54.939
<i>so this is kind of</i>
<i>out of my comfort zone.</i>

37:54.939 --> 37:58.067
<i>But after some light sanding,</i>
<i>it's gonna be done.</i>

37:58.067 --> 38:00.779
So I'm ready to go
cut something.

38:00.779 --> 38:02.447
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:02.447 --> 38:05.074
Whoo.
That's sharp.

38:05.074 --> 38:07.035
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:07.035 --> 38:09.412
‐ Josh, Ben, welcome back
to The Forge.

38:09.412 --> 38:11.581
You fellas have had four days
at your home forges

38:11.581 --> 38:13.041
to work on your Ram Daos.

38:13.041 --> 38:15.460
Josh, tell us about your blade.

38:15.460 --> 38:16.836
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:16.836 --> 38:20.423
<i>‐ I used 5160,</i>
<i>and for the handle,</i>

38:20.423 --> 38:21.966
<i>amboyna burl.</i>

38:21.966 --> 38:23.968
<i>The disk, I used brass,</i>

38:23.968 --> 38:26.346
<i>and aluminum finial.</i>

38:26.346 --> 38:28.431
‐ The whole sword assembly
is beautiful.

38:28.431 --> 38:29.849
Thank you for all that
hard work.

38:29.849 --> 38:31.392
All right, Ben.
You're up.

38:31.392 --> 38:33.311
Tell the judges
about your work.

38:33.311 --> 38:34.854
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:34.854 --> 38:36.815
<i>‐ I forged my blade</i>
<i>out of leaf spring.</i>

38:36.815 --> 38:41.653
<i>The handle is red oak with</i>
<i>mild steel for the fittings.</i>

38:41.653 --> 38:44.656
‐ All right, gentlemen,
one of these weapons belongs

38:44.656 --> 38:46.366
to the "Forged in Fire"
champion,

38:46.366 --> 38:48.326
and to find out who that is,
we're gonna put them

38:48.326 --> 38:49.536
through a series
of three tests.

38:49.536 --> 38:50.745
There will be a strength test,

38:50.745 --> 38:52.831
a sharpness test, and up first,

38:52.831 --> 38:54.833
the KEAL test.

38:54.833 --> 38:58.503
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
welcome to the KEAL test.

38:58.503 --> 39:00.964
Ram Dao, ram carcass.

39:00.964 --> 39:02.507
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:02.507 --> 39:04.843
Josh, you're up first.
You ready for this?

39:04.843 --> 39:06.511
‐ Well, let's kill it again.

39:06.511 --> 39:08.471
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:08.471 --> 39:12.058
Doug is holding my Ram Dao,
and I'm just thinking

39:12.058 --> 39:14.686
<i>just chop that head off.</i>
<i>Just chop it.</i>

39:14.686 --> 39:19.524
My heart is just pumping
10,000 miles per hour, man.

39:21.025 --> 39:25.989
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:25.989 --> 39:27.866
‐ Oh, my God.

39:27.866 --> 39:35.039
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:36.207 --> 39:39.878
‐ Oh, my God.
‐ [laughs]

39:39.878 --> 39:41.129
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:41.129 --> 39:42.630
‐ All right, Josh,
let's talk about

39:42.630 --> 39:44.757
your Ram Dao here.
The blade you have here

39:44.757 --> 39:48.261
is sharp.
For every pass it makes,

39:48.261 --> 39:51.097
it cuts deeply, but I also love

39:51.097 --> 39:53.099
what you have here
in sense of balance.

39:53.099 --> 39:54.601
Even though
it's a chopper,

39:54.601 --> 39:56.769
the recovery is
just comfortable enough

39:56.769 --> 39:58.897
to where you can cut
all the way through.

39:58.897 --> 40:00.982
It feels good in the hand,
it's got a great balance,

40:00.982 --> 40:04.444
and most importantly,
it will KEAL.

40:04.444 --> 40:06.738
Good job.
‐ That's awesome, thank you.

40:06.738 --> 40:08.072
‐ All right, Ben,
it's your turn.

40:08.072 --> 40:09.240
You ready for this?
‐ I'm excited.

40:09.240 --> 40:11.576
Let's do it.

40:11.576 --> 40:14.454
<i>Right now, I'm really excited.</i>
<i>I put my best work into this.</i>

40:14.454 --> 40:16.915
<i>Nothing's perfect,</i>
<i>but my biggest concern</i>

40:16.915 --> 40:19.083
is that there was
a slight warp

40:19.083 --> 40:20.627
<i>that I just really</i>
<i>couldn't get out.</i>

40:20.627 --> 40:22.754
<i>So I'm really hoping</i>
<i>that my blade</i>

40:22.754 --> 40:24.797
<i>outperforms Josh's</i>
<i>in every other way</i>

40:24.797 --> 40:28.760
so that it's a flaw
that can be overlooked.

40:28.760 --> 40:31.429
‐ Something's off
about this design.

40:31.429 --> 40:34.432
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:34.432 --> 40:36.267
‐ [whispering indistinctly]

40:38.603 --> 40:40.939
<i>‐ At this point,</i>
<i>I'm a bit confused.</i>

40:40.939 --> 40:42.357
<i>I don't know what's going on.</i>

40:42.357 --> 40:49.113
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:49.113 --> 40:51.616
‐ Ben, your blade doesn't have
a finial ball.

40:51.616 --> 40:54.786
It's one of the defining
characteristics of the Ram Dao.

40:54.786 --> 40:56.454
It was also
one of the parameters.

40:56.454 --> 40:58.122
And the judges feel
that your blade

40:58.122 --> 41:01.542
cannot be tested evenly
and fairly with Josh's.

41:01.542 --> 41:03.294
Dave Baker's
gonna tell you why.

41:03.294 --> 41:05.672
‐ The design of the Ram Dao
has that finial

41:05.672 --> 41:07.131
at the end of the blade.

41:07.131 --> 41:09.008
The finial can wind up being
a cut restrictor,

41:09.008 --> 41:11.135
not allowing the blade
to pass through a target.

41:11.135 --> 41:13.638
It also keeps that blade
from being able to stab.

41:13.638 --> 41:16.933
Yours doesn't have that.
How can we test them evenly?

41:16.933 --> 41:19.060
‐ I understand.
‐ Ben, "Forged in Fire"

41:19.060 --> 41:21.020
champions don't miss
parameters.

41:21.020 --> 41:22.981
I'd like to invite you
to shake our hands,

41:22.981 --> 41:24.273
shake your competitor's hand,

41:24.273 --> 41:26.734
and then please leave
The Forge.

41:26.734 --> 41:29.487
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:29.487 --> 41:32.490
‐ I'm pretty disappointed.
I really wanted to see my blade

41:32.490 --> 41:35.493
chop through that ram,
but I'm happy

41:35.493 --> 41:37.912
with what I turned in,
and at the end of the day,

41:37.912 --> 41:39.831
I think I'm definitely leaving
a better bladesmith

41:39.831 --> 41:41.416
<i>than when I came in.</i>

41:41.416 --> 41:44.168
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:44.168 --> 41:45.503
‐ Josh, congratulations.

41:45.503 --> 41:47.171
You're the "Forged in Fire"
champion,

41:47.171 --> 41:49.757
and that's a title that comes
with a check for $10,000.

41:49.757 --> 41:52.301
Come on forward and shake
our hands, brother.

41:52.301 --> 41:54.846
<i>‐ I cannot believe</i>
<i>this is happening.</i>

41:54.846 --> 41:57.223
I think what I'm gonna do
with $10,000

41:57.223 --> 42:00.685
<i>is gonna go to open a shop</i>
<i>where I'm gonna be providing</i>

42:00.685 --> 42:03.646
workshops for at‐risk youth.

42:03.646 --> 42:08.526
<i>My</i> abuelita <i>told me,</i>
<i>"Go, win, and come back."</i>

42:08.526 --> 42:09.944
Mission accomplished.

42:09.944 --> 42:16.951
<i>♪ ♪</i>
